document_data.Trade:
The [[gemstone chaka]] was native to Ormpé.{{cite book/The Shining South (1993)|56}} Gnomes were a common sight in the city.{{cite book/The Shining South (1993)|57}} So was the [[Finglefall]] chaka.{{cite book/The Shining South (1993)|}} The field glass was an invention of the gnomes of the city.{{cite book/The Shining South (1993)|60}}

Most of the people in the Quarter of No Hope were migrant grain workers, though some tried to obtain mining jobs, which paid better. However, the Gemstone chaka preferred to hire dwarven miners and gnomish gemcutters, having come to an agreement with the Finglefall chaka: whoever wanted to work on the famous Curna emeralds needed to come to an agreement with at least one of those chakas. However, several chakas had made their fortunes with the sale of gemstones by {{yearlink|1372}}.

A lot of scholars lodged at the city on the way to use the Library of Curna.{{cite book/The Shining South (1993)|66}}

document_data.History:
Ormpé was another fishing village that grew into a trade hub{{cite book/Shining South|123}} before it was conquered by [[beholder]] princes in the {{yearlinkName|147}}. These beholders were defeated by [[demons]] come from the [[Curna Mountains]] in the {{yearlinkName|153}}.{{cite book/Shining South|117}} The leader of the demons was a nasty [[ghour demon]].{{cite book/Shining South|118}} when the forces of [[Var]], [[Durpar]] and [[Estagund]] defeated the demons and forced their leader into flight; it was rumoured he took up with the local [[hill giant]]s.

An influx of people started around {{yearlink|1365}}, doubling the population by {{yearlink|1367}}. The influx of people had gone well beyond even what the local ruling council expected: Ormpé developed a rather large slum. By {{yearlink|1373}}, it was expected things would turn ugly if the squalor was left unaddressed.

Ormpé had fallen into the [[Golden Water]] by {{yearlink|1479}} DR.{{cite book/Forgotten Realms Campaign Guide|129}}
